    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also want to make sure the weave is tight enough to prevent any structural issues during the finishing process. if the density is too low, do you think we'll run into problems with the fabric being too porous or losing its shape easily? i'm mostly concerned about maintaining a tight, protective barrier for the fibers so they don't fray or degrade too quickly under tension.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the density is too low, the fabric will indeed be more porous, which can lead to structural vulnerabilities, especially under the stresses of finishing. Low density makes the structure weaker, meaning it has a higher risk of snagging, premature wear, and poor shape retention when tension is applied. A higher pick count helps create a more robust interlacing of warp and weft, essentially creating a tighter, more protective lattice for the fibers.",
      "source": "target",
